article.description: Paul Pierce scored 33 points as the Boston Celtics atoned for one of their most dubious losses with an 81-71 victory over the Detroit Pistons on Saturday night.
article.headline: Celtics atone for worst-ever loss, beating Pistons on road
article.linkText: Pistons fall prey to hot-shooting Pierce, Celtics
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Six weeks after enduring one of the more embarrassing defeats in team history -- at home, no less -- the Boston Celtics erased that ugly memory on the road. Paul Pierce scored 33 points and Antoine Walker had 17 as the Celtics beat the Detroit Pistons 81-71 Saturday night. It was the first meeting between the teams since Detroit won 118-66 on Jan. 31 -- the most lopsided defeat in the Celtics' long history. The 52-point margin also was the largest in the Pistons' history. "This was a big win,'' said Pierce, whose team has won seven of 10. "We were able to bounce back and get a win in a tough environment where teams rarely get wins.'' Celtics coach Jim O'Brien tried to play down the revenge angle, saying his team hadn't even discussed it, but his other All-Star contradicted him. "We were very focused from the beginning, because this team beat us by 52 points and we felt like they tried to run the score up on us a little bit,'' Walker said. "I think they got a little false security from that game.'' Chauncey Billups scored 19 points and Ben Wallace had 21 rebounds to lead Detroit, which had won four straight. "It was a hard-played game, and Boston was just better than us tonight,'' Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "We knew they were going to be fired up. You get beat by that number of points, and it is just natural to come out hard the next time.'' Richard Hamilton scored just eight points on 3-of-15 shooting. Hamilton is shooting 30.7 percent (20-65) in the last four games. "You play a different style of basketball when you're making a run for the playoffs, and I've never been in that situation before,'' Hamilton said. "I just haven't been able to get into a rhythm this week, but I have to play through it and keep shooting.'' Boston led by as many as 16 in the first half and still had a 48-37 edge at the break, thanks to 14 points from Pierce. After Wallace's dunk to open the second half, Pierce converted two straight three-point plays to put the Celtics up 54-39. Hamilton scored the next eight, his only points of the night, to get the Pistons back into the game. Pierce and Walker combined to score all 13 of the Celtics' points in the third quarter, and Detroit trailed only 61-57 heading into the fourth. The Pistons were still within four when Corliss Williamson was called for a flagrant foul on Pierce. He hit both free throws, then hit a short jumper after the inbounds pass, putting Boston up 73-65 with six minutes left. Detroit didn't get closer than four the rest of the way. "This is a very important win for our ballclub, because we beat a hell of a team in the Pistons,'' O'Brien said. "This is a good rivalry that we have with the Pistons; we've had a lot of hard-fought games.''

Game notes
Hamilton, who missed 15 straight shots over a span of two games earlier in the week, missed his first 10 on Saturday night. ... The Celtics' win was just the third in their last 14 trips to Detroit. ... Boston was called for three defensive three-second technicals, but Billups missed all three free throws. ... Wallace is averaging 21.3 rebounds over his last four games. He also became the first player to get 20 rebounds in three straight games since Dikembe Mutombo did it from Dec. 26-29, 2000. Wilt Chamberlain holds the NBA record with 21 in a row. ... The Celtics scored the first nine points of the game and never trailed.
